<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIES AND REFLECTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 12 10:56:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I don’t know if it matters . . . I was a college student in the late 60s and for what it’s worth, even though I did not serve in Vietnam, I have many, many memories that are connected to people I will never see again: my high school boyfriend, John Evans, left his family forever and disappeared in Canada; one cousin of mine was killed, Dennis Cannan and one returned, Joel Stevens; two friends were COs, Allen Taubman and Eric Porter; I said farewell to Carl Berman at Fort Dix; wished Rolfe Pottinger and Arnold Zuboff the best as they disappeared; in 1969 watched returned vet Eddie deJesus, security guard in the store I worked in, call out “Stop, or I shoot” when he tracked a shoplifter to an alley outside the store in Rochester, N.Y. <br>
 <br>
I marched in the Mobilization to End the War in NYC, felt it was my response to the escalating violence, not to the politics that leaders of both sides used for their own purposes. . . . I prayed, worried, was traumatized by newspaper accounts and still cannot see Platoon.<br><br>
Whether violence is sanctioned by the government or is an act of self-defense of a soldier in the field, all choice, self-control, sacredness, respect, humanity dissolves in its wake.  I think those who were not in the war often lived it anyway.  Perhaps the “protests” were a last ditch attempt by a populace to say “I am in this, too. . . . Violence destroys me as well.”<br><br>
My own feeling is that what is less significant than the negative name-calling that followed vets home, is the fact that they were not supported in their grief, but had to wait 20+ years to plunge wholeheartedly into the heart of the pain.  The grief then is more difficult because of the intervening memories which often are also of loss.<br><br>
My prayer for Vietnam-era vets and their families is that they will share those experiences with others. They are a source of understanding and, hopefully, compassion.  They were forced to live violently, much like those in abusive relationships.  Their “relationship” with the armed service they served in may have been in many cases forced, abusive in its intent, and deeply defining in their lives.<br>

